WEBVTT

00:02.180 --> 00:04.480
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:04.960 --> 00:07.100
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:07.820 --> 00:12.700
For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:14.640 --> 00:17.340
End of Green Gables by Lucy Maud Montgomery.

00:18.520 --> 00:19.860
Chapter 27.

00:20.880 --> 00:22.860
Vanity and vexation of spirit.

00:24.740 --> 00:29.420
Marilla, walking home one late April afternoon from an aid meeting, realized that the winter

00:29.420 --> 00:34.220
was over and gone with the thrill of delight that spring never fails to bring to the oldest

00:34.220 --> 00:37.380
and saddest as well as the youngest and merriest.

00:38.360 --> 00:41.860
Marilla was not given to subjective analysis of her thoughts and feelings.

00:42.820 --> 00:47.960
She probably imagined that she was thinking about the aides and their missionary box and

00:47.960 --> 00:49.600
the new carpet for their vestry room.

00:50.400 --> 00:55.980
But under these reflections was a harmonious consciousness of red fields smoking into pale

00:55.980 --> 01:02.340
purpley mists in the declining sun, of long sharp pointed fur shadows following over the

01:02.340 --> 01:09.580
meadow beyond the brook, of still crimson-butted maples around a mirror-like wood pool, of

01:09.580 --> 01:13.500
awakening in a world and the stir of hidden pulses under the gray sod.

01:15.380 --> 01:20.900
The spring was abroad in the land and Marilla's sober, middle-aged step was lighter and swifter

01:20.900 --> 01:23.300
because of its deep primal gladness.

01:24.620 --> 01:30.660
Her eyes swelled affectionately on Green Gables, peering through its network of trees and reflecting

01:30.660 --> 01:35.060
the sunlight back from its windows in several little coruscations of glory.

01:35.860 --> 01:41.420
Marilla, as she picked her steps along the damp lane, thought that it was really a satisfaction

01:41.420 --> 01:46.920
to know that she was going home to a briskly snapping wood fire and a table nicely spread

01:46.920 --> 01:52.920
for tea instead of to the cold comfort of old aid meetings before Anne had come to Green

01:52.920 --> 01:53.300
Gables.

01:56.580 --> 02:02.020
Consequently, when Marilla entered her kitchen and found the fire black out, with no sign

02:02.020 --> 02:05.920
of Anne anywhere, she felt justly disappointed and irritated.

02:06.940 --> 02:11.840
She had told Anne to be sure and have tea ready at five o'clock, but now she must hurry

02:11.840 --> 02:16.580
to take off her second-best dress and prepare the meal herself against Matthew's returning

02:16.580 --> 02:17.240
from plowing.

02:20.100 --> 02:25.260
I'll settle Miss Anne when she comes home, said Marilla grimly, as she shaved up kindlings

02:25.260 --> 02:28.920
with a carving knife and with more vim than was strictly necessary.

02:30.680 --> 02:33.820
Matthew had come in and was waiting patiently for his tea in the corner.

02:35.040 --> 02:39.600
She's off gadding somewhere with Diana, writing stories or practicing dialogues or some such

02:39.600 --> 02:43.160
tomfoolery and never thinking once about the time or her duties.

02:44.120 --> 02:47.180
She's just got to be pulled up short and sudden on this sort of thing.

02:47.800 --> 02:51.940
I don't care if Mrs. Allen does say she's the brightest and sweetest child she ever knew.

02:52.580 --> 02:56.880
She may be bright and sweet enough, but her head is full of nonsense, and there's never

02:56.880 --> 02:59.180
any knowing what shape it'll break out in next.

03:00.080 --> 03:05.180
Just as soon as she grows out of one freak, she takes up another, but there, here I am

03:05.180 --> 03:08.860
saying the very thing I was so riled with Rachel Lynn for saying at the aid today.

03:08.860 --> 03:14.620
I was really glad when Mrs. Allen spoke up for Anne, for if she hadn't, I know I'd have

03:14.620 --> 03:17.260
had said something too sharp to Rachel before everybody.

03:18.320 --> 03:23.560
Anne's got plenty of faults, goodness knows, and far be it for me to deny it, but I'm bringing

03:23.560 --> 03:28.920
her up, and not Rachel Lynn, who'd pick faults in the angel Gabriel himself if he lived in

03:28.920 --> 03:29.620
Avonlea.

03:30.280 --> 03:34.280
Just the same, Anne has no business to leave the house like this when I told her she must

03:34.280 --> 03:36.740
stay home this afternoon and look after things.

03:37.380 --> 03:42.880
I must say, with all her faults, I never found her disobedient or untrustworthy before, and

03:42.880 --> 03:44.740
I'm real sorry to find her so now.

03:46.640 --> 03:53.980
Well now, I don't know, said Matthew, who, being patient and wise and, above all, hungry,

03:54.700 --> 03:59.380
had deemed it best to let Marilla talk her wrath out unhindered, having learned by experience

03:59.380 --> 04:03.860
that she got through with whatever work was on hand much quicker, if not delayed by untimely

04:03.860 --> 04:04.380
argument.

04:05.560 --> 04:08.280
Perhaps you're judging her too hastily, Marilla.

04:09.200 --> 04:13.000
Don't call her untrustworthy until you're sure she's disobeyed you.

04:13.600 --> 04:16.920
Maybe it can be all explained, Anne's a great hand at explaining.

04:18.660 --> 04:21.580
She's not here when I told her to stay, retorted Marilla.

04:22.120 --> 04:25.400
I reckon she'll find it hard to explain that to my satisfaction.

04:26.540 --> 04:30.440
Of course I knew you'd take her part, Matthew, but I'm bringing her up, not you.

04:32.680 --> 04:38.000
It was dark when supper was ready, and still no sign of Anne, coming hurriedly over the

04:38.000 --> 04:42.440
log bridge or up Lovers Lane, breathless and repentant with a sense of neglected duties.

04:43.720 --> 04:45.800
Marilla washed and put away the dishes grimly.

04:46.260 --> 04:51.140
Then, wanting a candle to light her way down the cellar, she went up to the east gable

04:51.140 --> 04:53.420
for the one that generally stood on Anne's table.

04:54.320 --> 04:59.020
Lighting it, she turned around to see Anne herself lying on the bed, face downward among

04:59.020 --> 04:59.560
the pillows.

05:01.240 --> 05:03.600
Mercy on us, said astonished Marilla.

05:04.120 --> 05:05.300
Have you been asleep, Anne?

05:06.380 --> 05:08.660
No, was a muffled reply.

05:09.520 --> 05:10.640
Are you sick then?

05:11.260 --> 05:14.220
Dermended Marilla anxiously, going over to the bed.

05:15.300 --> 05:20.180
Anne cowered deeper into her pillows as if desirous of hiding herself forever from mortal

05:20.180 --> 05:20.680
eyes.

05:21.700 --> 05:26.640
No, but please, Marilla, go away and don't look at me.

05:26.640 --> 05:31.660
I'm in the depths of despair, and I don't care who gets ahead in class or writes the

05:31.660 --> 05:34.940
best compositions or sings in the Sunday school choir anymore.

05:35.800 --> 05:39.880
Little things like that are of no importance now, because I don't suppose I'll ever be

05:39.880 --> 05:41.200
able to go anywhere again.

05:41.820 --> 05:43.000
My career is closed.

05:43.620 --> 05:46.200
Please, Marilla, go away and don't look at me.

05:47.480 --> 05:51.540
Did anyone ever hear the like the mystified Marilla wanted to know?

05:52.100 --> 05:54.580
And Shirley, whatever is the matter with you?

05:54.740 --> 05:55.520
What have you done?

05:56.340 --> 05:58.180
Get right up this minute and tell me.

05:58.400 --> 05:59.620
This minute, I say.

06:00.060 --> 06:00.700
There now.

06:00.900 --> 06:01.980
What is it?

06:03.220 --> 06:05.820
Anne had slid to the floor in despairing obedience.

06:06.780 --> 06:10.460
Look at my hair, Marilla, she whispered.

06:12.620 --> 06:18.040
Accordingly, Marilla lifted her candle and looked scrutinizingly at Anne's hair, flowing

06:18.040 --> 06:19.580
in heavy masses down her back.

06:20.360 --> 06:22.680
It certainly had a very strange appearance.

06:24.040 --> 06:27.480
Anne Shirley, what have you done to your hair?

06:28.020 --> 06:30.120
Why, it's green.

06:31.740 --> 06:39.460
Green it might be called, if it were any earthly color, a queer, dull, bronzy green with streaks

06:39.460 --> 06:43.180
here and there of the original red to highlight the ghastly effect.

06:44.180 --> 06:49.720
Never in all her life had Marilla seen anything so grotesque as Anne's hair at that moment.

06:50.780 --> 06:53.100
Yes, it's green, moaned Anne.

06:53.860 --> 06:59.180
I thought nothing could be as bad as red hair, but now I know it's ten times worse to have

06:59.180 --> 06:59.880
green hair.

07:00.620 --> 07:04.600
Oh, Marilla, you little know how utterly wretched I am.

07:06.160 --> 07:09.940
I little know how you got into this fix, but I mean to find out, said Marilla.

07:10.520 --> 07:14.360
Come right down to the kitchen, it's too cold up here, and tell me just what you've done.

07:14.840 --> 07:17.500
I've been expecting something queer for some time now.

07:17.500 --> 07:21.840
You haven't gotten into any scrape for over two months, and I was sure another one was due.

07:22.320 --> 07:24.580
Now then, what did you do to your hair?

07:26.080 --> 07:26.960
I dyed it.

07:28.320 --> 07:29.100
Died it?

07:29.440 --> 07:30.340
Died your hair?

07:30.960 --> 07:34.580
And Shirley, didn't you know it was a wicked thing to do?

07:35.840 --> 07:41.380
Yes, I knew it was a little wicked, admitted Anne, but I thought it was worthwhile to be

07:41.380 --> 07:43.240
a little wicked to get rid of red hair.

07:44.020 --> 07:45.460
I counted the cost, Marilla.

07:46.120 --> 07:49.400
Besides, I meant to be extra good in other ways to make up for it.

07:50.460 --> 07:55.460
Well, said Marilla sarcastically, if I had decided it was worthwhile to dye my hair,

07:55.560 --> 07:57.200
I'd have dyed it a decent color at least.

07:57.300 --> 07:58.440
I wouldn't have dyed it green.

07:59.840 --> 08:03.860
But I didn't mean to dye it green, Marilla, protested Anne dejectedly.

08:04.760 --> 08:07.480
If I was wicked, I meant to be wicked to some purpose.

08:08.200 --> 08:10.680
He said it would turn my hair a beautiful raven black.

08:11.080 --> 08:13.140
He positively assured me that it would.

08:13.780 --> 08:15.300
How could I doubt his word, Marilla?

08:15.980 --> 08:18.640
I know what it feels like to have your word doubted.

08:18.860 --> 08:23.500
And Mrs. Allen says we should never suspect anyone of not telling us the truth unless

08:23.500 --> 08:24.920
we have proof that they're not.

08:26.060 --> 08:27.300
I have proof now.

08:27.840 --> 08:29.440
Green hair is proof enough for anybody.

08:30.300 --> 08:34.500
But I hadn't then, and I believed every word he said implicitly.

08:36.400 --> 08:37.060
Who said?

08:37.660 --> 08:38.700
Who are you talking about?

08:39.600 --> 08:41.500
The peddler that was here this afternoon.

08:41.500 --> 08:43.120
I bought the dye from him.

08:44.320 --> 08:45.140
And Shirley.

08:46.020 --> 08:49.680
How often have I told you never to let one of those Italians in the house?

08:50.000 --> 08:52.660
I don't believe in encouraging them to come around at all.

08:53.880 --> 08:55.700
Oh, I didn't let him in the house.

08:56.140 --> 09:00.640
I remember what you told me, and I went out, carefully shut the door, and looked at his

09:00.640 --> 09:01.400
things on the step.

09:02.040 --> 09:04.000
Besides, he wasn't an Italian.

09:04.180 --> 09:05.300
He was a German Jew.

09:05.840 --> 09:10.760
He had a big box full of very interesting things, and told me he was working hard to

09:10.760 --> 09:13.760
make enough money to bring his wife and children out from Germany.

09:14.540 --> 09:17.960
He spoke so feelingly about them that it touched my heart.

09:18.480 --> 09:22.040
I wanted to buy something from him to help him in such a worthy object.

09:22.780 --> 09:24.720
Then all at once I saw the bottle of hair dye.

09:25.380 --> 09:30.460
The peddler said it was warranted to dye any hair a beautiful raven black and wouldn't

09:30.460 --> 09:31.280
wash off.

09:32.280 --> 09:38.240
In a trice, I saw myself with beautiful raven black hair, and the temptation was irresistible.

09:38.700 --> 09:42.860
But the price of the bottle was seventy-five cents, and I only had fifty cents left out

09:42.860 --> 09:43.620
of my chicken money.

09:44.640 --> 09:50.040
I think the peddler had a very kind heart, for he said that, seeing it was me, he'd

09:50.040 --> 09:52.680
sell it for fifty cents, and that was just giving it away.

09:53.620 --> 09:57.800
So I bought it, and as soon as I had gone up here and applied it with an old hairbrush,

09:57.900 --> 10:03.940
as the direction said, I used up the whole bottle, and oh, Marilla, when I saw the dreadful

10:03.940 --> 10:07.840
color that had turned my hair, I repented of being wicked, I can tell you, and I've

10:07.840 --> 10:09.160
been repenting ever since.

10:11.600 --> 10:15.980
Well, I hope you'll repent to good purpose, said Marilla severely, and that you've got

10:15.980 --> 10:18.600
your eyes open to where your vanity has led you, Anne.

10:19.060 --> 10:20.660
Goodness knows what's to be done.

10:21.000 --> 10:24.160
I suppose the first thing to do is give your hair a good washing and see if it will do

10:24.160 --> 10:24.720
any good.

10:26.160 --> 10:31.120
Accordingly, Anne washed her hair, scrubbing it vigorously with soap and water, but for

10:31.120 --> 10:34.300
all the difference it made, she might as well have been scouring its original red.

10:34.300 --> 10:38.780
The peddler had certainly spoken the truth when he declared the dye wouldn't wash off.

10:39.140 --> 10:41.840
However, his veracity might be impeached in other respects.

10:43.280 --> 10:45.480
Oh, Marilla, what shall I do?

10:45.840 --> 10:47.120
questioned Anne in tears.

10:47.700 --> 10:49.240
I can never live this down.

10:49.900 --> 10:54.720
People have pretty well forgotten my other mistakes, the liniment kink and setting Diana

10:54.720 --> 10:59.440
drunk and flying into a temper with Mrs. Linde, but they'll never forget this.

11:00.040 --> 11:01.620
They will think I'm not respectable.

11:01.620 --> 11:07.740
Oh, Marilla, what a tangled web we weave when first we practice to deceive.

11:08.460 --> 11:10.280
That is poetry, but it is true.

11:10.740 --> 11:13.660
And oh, how Josie Pye will laugh.

11:14.220 --> 11:17.220
Marilla, I cannot face Josie Pye.

11:17.780 --> 11:20.540
I'm the unhappiest girl in Prince Edward Island.

11:22.640 --> 11:24.720
Anne's unhappiness continued for a week.

11:25.440 --> 11:28.540
During that time, she went nowhere and shampooed her hair every day.

11:29.340 --> 11:34.700
Diana alone of outsiders knew the fatal secret, but she promised solemnly never to tell,

11:35.220 --> 11:37.820
and it may be stated here now that she kept her word.

11:38.960 --> 11:41.260
At the end of the week, Marilla said decidedly,

11:41.860 --> 11:42.960
It's no use, Anne.

11:43.620 --> 11:45.540
This is fast dye if there ever was any.

11:45.820 --> 11:46.820
Your hair must be cut off.

11:46.960 --> 11:47.880
There is no other way.

11:48.220 --> 11:50.040
You can't go out with it looking like that.

11:51.260 --> 11:55.220
Anne's lips quivered, but she realized the bitter truth of Marilla's remarks.

11:55.800 --> 11:58.220
With a dismal sigh, she went for the scissors.

11:59.880 --> 12:02.460
Please cut it off at once, Marilla, and have it over.

12:03.040 --> 12:05.020
Oh, I feel that my heart is broken.

12:05.720 --> 12:07.480
This is such an unromantic affliction.

12:08.240 --> 12:12.160
The girls in books lose their hair in fevers or sell it to get money for some good dean,

12:12.560 --> 12:16.020
and I'm sure I wouldn't mind losing my hair in such a fashion half so much.

12:16.820 --> 12:21.860
But there is nothing comforting in having your hair cut off because you've dyed it a dreadful color, is there?

12:22.480 --> 12:26.120
I'm going to weep all the time you're cutting it off, if it won't interfere.

12:27.060 --> 12:28.800
It seems such a tragic thing.

12:30.920 --> 12:36.120
Anne wept then, but later on, when she went upstairs and looked in the glass, she was calm with despair.

12:37.080 --> 12:42.200
Marilla had done her work thoroughly, and it had been necessary to shingle the hair as closely as possible.

12:43.060 --> 12:46.820
The result was not becoming, to state the case as mildly as may be.

12:47.520 --> 12:49.600
Anne promptly turned her glass to the wall.

12:50.400 --> 12:54.860
I'll never, never look at myself again until my hair grows, she exclaimed passionately.

12:56.080 --> 12:57.760
Then suddenly she righted the glass.

12:58.840 --> 13:02.400
Yes, I will, too. I'll do penance for being wicked that way.

13:02.720 --> 13:06.480
I'll look at myself every time I come into my room and see how ugly I am.

13:06.840 --> 13:09.000
And I won't try to imagine it away, either.

13:09.560 --> 13:15.280
I never thought I was vain about my hair, of all things, but now I know I was, in spite of its being red,

13:15.740 --> 13:17.740
because it was so long and thick and curly.

13:18.380 --> 13:22.280
I expect something will happen to my nose next.

13:23.820 --> 13:26.700
Anne's clipped head made a sensation in school on the following Monday,

13:27.260 --> 13:31.080
but to her relief nobody guessed the real reason for it, not even Josie Pye,

13:31.620 --> 13:36.160
who, however, did not fail to inform Anne that she looked like a perfect scarecrow.

13:37.700 --> 13:40.240
I didn't say anything when Josie said that to me.

13:40.440 --> 13:44.720
Anne confided that evening to Marilla, who was lying on the sofa after one of her headaches,

13:44.720 --> 13:48.560
because I thought it was part of my punishment, and I ought to bear it patiently.

13:49.620 --> 13:55.680
It's hard to be told you look like a scarecrow, and I wanted to say something back, but I didn't.

13:56.000 --> 13:59.600
I just swept her one of my scornful looks, and then I forgave her.

13:59.960 --> 14:03.540
It makes you feel very virtuous when you forgive people, doesn't it?

14:04.480 --> 14:10.100
I mean to devote all my energies to being good after this, and I shall never try to be beautiful again.

14:10.720 --> 14:12.760
Of course, it's better to be good.

14:12.760 --> 14:17.560
I know it is, but sometimes it's so hard to believe a thing even when you know it.

14:18.080 --> 14:24.740
I do really want to be good, Marilla, like you and Mrs. Allen and Miss Stacy, and grow up to be a credit to you.

14:25.360 --> 14:31.020
Diana says, when my hair begins to grow, to tie a black velvet ribbon around my head with a bow at one side.

14:31.880 --> 14:33.520
She says she thinks it will be very becoming.

14:34.320 --> 14:37.200
I will call it a snood. That sounds so romantic.

14:38.100 --> 14:41.000
But am I talking too much, Marilla? Does it hurt your head?

14:42.880 --> 14:44.420
My head is better now.

14:44.840 --> 14:46.880
It was terrible by this afternoon, though.

14:47.220 --> 14:49.100
These headaches of mine are getting worse and worse.

14:49.620 --> 14:51.400
I'll have to see a doctor about them.

14:51.840 --> 14:54.680
As for your chatter, I don't know that I mind it.

14:54.900 --> 14:56.420
I've got so used to it.

14:57.780 --> 15:01.940
Which was Marilla's way of saying that she liked to hear it.

15:08.000 --> 15:09.380
End of chapter 27

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
Recorded by Susan Hooks, Tokyo, Japan

